\fs29\fsmilli14950 \cf4 \cb3 The\'a0relationship between print and poetry in the period from\'a0
\i Paradise Lost
\i0 \'a0to\'a0
\i Lyrical Ballads
\i0 \'a0was an uneasy one. On poetry\'92s side, the link with a vocal performance and with the freedom and expressivity of manuscript circulation was still strong, and it was accompanied by a deep mistrust of compromise with the commercial demands of print.{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www-oxfordhandbooks-com.myaccess.library.utoronto.ca/view/10.1093/oxfordhb/9780199600809.001.0001/oxfordhb-9780199600809-e-3#oxfordhb-9780199600809-e-3-note-91"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs22\fsmilli11212 \cf5 \strokec5 1}}\'a0On print\'92s side, poetry was always going to be troublesome, because its frequent brevity and persistent demands on paper created difficulties in shaping it into something saleable. Prestige attached itself to the publication of great poems, but reference books, religious and political controversy, plays, and, late in the period, novels were a better financial bet. The sheer awkwardness of this relationship, however, generated a period of diversity and experiment.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl340\sa299\partightenfactor0
\cf4 \cb3 What could be done to represent the human voice through the resources of the compositor\'92s case was tried, though it risked charges of diseconomy and inelegance. The beauties of manuscript publication were mimicked in large illustrated and ornamented quartos and folios, while some of its casualness was echoed in slips and half-sheets. In a counter move, poems played with the bookishness of their embodiment, toying with the dignity of the Bible or the classical variorum, or with the antique in the form of prophecy or medieval lyrics. The book trade\'92s most significant innovation, alongside the magazine and the miscellany, was to make the poetry book a luxury item, paying its way by using up more and better paper than it strictly needed in order to command a higher price. Although this practice moderated in the course of the century, it remained an influence in poetry publication, as it does today. As Roger Lonsdale notes in his pioneering\'a0
\i New Oxford Book of Eighteenth-Century Verse
\i0 , late in the century booksellers turned poems themselves into vast reference collections, anthologizing the age\'92s verse and deciding which authors merited reprinting.{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www-oxfordhandbooks-com.myaccess.library.utoronto.ca/view/10.1093/oxfordhb/9780199600809.001.0001/oxfordhb-9780199600809-e-3#oxfordhb-9780199600809-e-3-note-92"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs22\fsmilli11212 \cf5 \strokec5 2}}\'a0My account will follow the eighteenth-century editors\'92 lead and, with some exceptions, focus on the poetry that they were already making canonical.{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www-oxfordhandbooks-com.myaccess.library.utoronto.ca/view/10.1093/oxfordhb/9780199600809.001.0001/oxfordhb-9780199600809-e-3#oxfordhb-9780199600809-e-3-note-93"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs22\fsmilli11212 \cf5 \strokec5 3}}\cf6 \cb1  (40)
