\b\fs40 \cf2 \strokec2 Sales\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl340\sa299\partightenfactor0

\b0\fs29\fsmilli14950 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4 The popularity of large formats in the early eighteenth century doubtless reflects a desire for dignity, but another important reason for their prevalence was commercial. As David Foxon says of Pope\'92s folio\'a0
\i Windsor-Forest
\i0 \'a0and\'a0
\i Ode for Musick
\i0 , they were printed in \'93a format which would justify a price sufficient to make a profit\'97one shilling for\'a0
\i Windsor Forest
\i0 \'a0in five sheets, 6
\i d
\i0 . for the\'a0
\i Ode
\i0 \'a0in three.\'94{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www-oxfordhandbooks-com.myaccess.library.utoronto.ca/view/10.1093/oxfordhb/9780199600809.001.0001/oxfordhb-9780199600809-e-3#oxfordhb-9780199600809-e-3-note-105"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs22\fsmilli11212 \cf5 \strokec5 15}}\'a0The basic problem was that demand for poetry was relatively low. Even poems that enjoyed critical esteem did not have big sales. The first edition of a poem by Pope could be expected to sell 2,000 copies, and those not necessarily all at once. Woodfall\'92s ledgers show him printing 2,000 copies of the\'a0
\i First Epistle of the Second Book of Horace
\i0 \'a0(1737), with 150 fine-paper copies in addition, while Bowyer printed only 2,000 copies of the\'a0
\i New Dunciad
\i0 \'a0(1742), which might have been expected to be a bestseller.{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www-oxfordhandbooks-com.myaccess.library.utoronto.ca/view/10.1093/oxfordhb/9780199600809.001.0001/oxfordhb-9780199600809-e-3#oxfordhb-9780199600809-e-3-note-106"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs22\fsmilli11212 \cf5 \strokec5 16}}\'a0And I don\'92t think Pope sold badly. Bowyer printed 2,000 copies of Gray\'92s\'a0
\i Trivia
\i0 , with 250 fine, in January 1716 and needed to print only 1,000 of the second edition in June. William Somervile\'92s\'a0
\i The Chace
\i0 \'a0was a popular success, running to eight editions between 1735 and 1749, but the first edition, printed by Bowyer, was a quarto of only 750 copies, with an additional 500 on royal paper, while the second edition dropped to octavo and was of 1,000 copies; only the third, again octavo, at 1,500 suggests marked success. The fourth authorized edition was not needed until 1743, and consisted of only 500 copies.{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www-oxfordhandbooks-com.myaccess.library.utoronto.ca/view/10.1093/oxfordhb/9780199600809.001.0001/oxfordhb-9780199600809-e-3#oxfordhb-9780199600809-e-3-note-107"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs22\fsmilli11212 \cf5 \strokec5 17}}\'a0It is worth\'a0
\b\fs26 \cf7 \strokec7 (p. 47)\'a0
\b0\fs29\fsmilli14950 \cf4 \strokec4 noting that the sale of 6,000 copies of the octavo\'a0
\i Rape of the Lock
\i0 \'a0in six weeks was regarded as a phenomenal success.\cf6  (46-47)\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl440\sa400\partightenfactor0

\b\fs40 \cf2 \strokec2 The Luxury Poetry Book\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl340\sa299\partightenfactor0

\b0\fs29\fsmilli14950 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4 The credit for moving poetry to the luxury end of the book market, if it is credit, must go to Jacob Tonson, Sr. He saw that the bookseller\'92s financial problems could be solved not by printing as cheaply as possible, but by printing elegantly and charging a higher price.\
Tonson\'92s influence on the poetry book can be seen by comparing the first edition of\'a0
\i Paradise Lost
\i0 \'a0of 1667 with his edition of 1688. The first edition is printed without fuss, as though the poem is a slightly extravagant form of prose. The format is quarto, with the type set solid. Rules are used to surround the text tightly, with boxes to the upper and outer margins. The impression is of a religious text; the presentation, though without black letter and double columns, is not unlike that of the King James Bible.{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www-oxfordhandbooks-com.myaccess.library.utoronto.ca/view/10.1093/oxfordhb/9780199600809.001.0001/oxfordhb-9780199600809-e-3#oxfordhb-9780199600809-e-3-note-109"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs22\fsmilli11212 \cf5 \strokec5 19}}\'a0Tonson\'92s 1688 edition, undertaken jointly with Richard Bentley, is altogether more spacious, with Milton beginning to\'a0
\b\fs26 \cf7 \strokec7 (p. 48)\'a0
\b0\fs29\fsmilli14950 \cf4 \strokec4 be treated as a classic. The edition was marketed by subscription, a fusion of patronage and publication; in buying the book in advance you supported it with cash and with your name. The 1688\'a0
\i Paradise Lost
\i0 \'a0is a folio in fours, much more spacious than the quarto first edition, and it is illustrated.\cf6  (47-48)\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl440\sa400\partightenfactor0

\b\fs40 \cf2 \strokec2 Conclusion\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl340\sa299\partightenfactor0

\b0\fs29\fsmilli14950 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4 The most remarkable aspect of poems in print in this period is their sheer variety, and it is worth noting in conclusion how much poems differed in themselves. Print might be expected to have the effect of stabilizing poetic texts, but it has its own inbuilt tendency toward variation.{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www-oxfordhandbooks-com.myaccess.library.utoronto.ca/view/10.1093/oxfordhb/9780199600809.001.0001/oxfordhb-9780199600809-e-3#oxfordhb-9780199600809-e-3-note-120"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs22\fsmilli11212 \cf5 \strokec5 30}}\'a0Even if stop-press correction, prevalent in the early period, is put aside, there are opportunities for change through later editions, the correction and expansion of existing works, and the addition of introductory and explanatory apparatus. The initiative for such changes may often come from the author, but the book trade clearly has an interest in generating new copy and new sales.\cf6  (53)\
